&lt;br /></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-12-10</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>164813</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Partisanship, political constraints, and employment protection reforms in an era of austerity</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>881B9ED3-4ACE-4943-B7FA-38A827FAFAEC</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This talk focused on the question of why some governments adopt unpopular reforms entailing far-reaching liberalization of the labour market, while others opt only for marginal adjustments or even regulatory reforms. The presentation showed that the likelihood of different types of reform is an effect of different constellations of government partisanship and veto players. The talk generated a lively debate with a series of comments of questions from the audience.

This talk resulted in a paper that was subsequently published in the European Political Science Review in 2013.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other academic audiences (collaborators, peers etc.)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The consequences of labour market reform</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>C64096A6-0774-4FA6-B13E-33779E0F5F02</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This workshop, held in Brighton on 9 December 2011, served to disseminate some key findings from the project. The workshop was focused on the consequences of labour market reforms.

