Employment Performance, Employment Quality and Changing Social Risks', which I am co-editing with Colin Crouch (forthcoming March 2015).</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>paper presentation</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The politics and economics of employment protection</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>8190E5E2-6474-45FB-AF4D-7E4A1DA4E2A1</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The lecture outlined the main findings of the project up to that date. The lecture was focused on two issues: (1) Under what conditions do governments adopt politically costly employment protection reforms? and (2) Is employment protection legislation responsible for high unemployment?

The proceedings of the talk were published in the Newsletter and the Annual Report of the Hanse Institute for Advanced Studies, after which several researchers requested my data on employment protection reforms.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>5500</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>University of Sussex Research Development Fund</gtr:description><gtr:end>2015-04-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>University of Sussex</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>815728E1-0BB4-4F37-9475-04859902A3D6</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2015-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The project is comprised of three distinct parts that focus on various aspects of employment protection. The first is an analysis of the impact of EPL (employment protection legislation) and other labour market institutions on employment performance. This part of the project has resulted in two papers, one focusing on aggregate unemployment and the other on youth unemployment in the EU and OECD countries during the last three decades. Neither paper finds systematic support for the conventional view that unemployment is a consequence of rigid labour market institutions. The evidence is particularly weak if we consider only the direct effects of individual institutions. While we found some indications that certain institutional interactions may be important (such as between the tax wedge on the one hand, and unemployment benefits and employment protection on the other), this evidence is not unambiguously clear. Our analysis therefore challenges the policy orthodoxy that comprehensive labour market deregulation is necessary to reduce or stabilise unemployment. Calls for further labour market deregulation seem to be especially unwarranted in CEECs (Central and Eastern Europe), where the link between institutions and unemployment appears particularly weak. But even in the advanced economies the effects of institutions are weak and in most cases depend heavily on which countries are included in the analysis. The most plausible interpretation of these results is that institutions have different effects in different contexts, and that therefore there is no universal cause of (and remedy for) unemployment. An implication of this for further research is that in-depth analyses of individual countries or particular groups of countries may be more fruitful in offering sound policy recommendations than the continued search for universal causes of unemployment.



The second part of the project examines why some governments adopt unpopular reforms entailing far-reaching liberalisation of the labour market, while others opt only for marginal adjustments or even regulatory reforms. Focusing on EPL reforms in 24 EU countries during 1990-2007, the analysis shows that the likelihood of different types of reform is an effect of different constellations of government partisanship and veto players. Combining the 'blame avoidance' and 'veto players' logics of politics, the analysis demonstrates that veto players have either a constraining or enabling effect depending on the partisan orientation of government. Correspondingly, liberalisation is pursued either by right parties facing few veto players, or by left parties in contexts with a high degree of power sharing. Regulatory reforms are most likely when left governments enjoy strong power concentration, but marginal regulation may be also adopted under external (ie EU) pressure by right governments facing many veto players. 



The third part of the analysis examines the reasons behind cross-national variation in the strictness of EPL in CEECs. This analysis is still undergoing, but some preliminary findings suggest that there may be two different paths to high levels of employment protection, one involving strong labour movements and few veto players, and the other weak governments and a high degree of non-market coordination.</gtr:description><gtr:id>159A0386-7A69-4327-9195-C54F4AD192BB</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Education,Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:description>This database offers annual series of the EPL index, a measure of the strictness of employment protection legislation, for Central and Eastern European (CEE) countries during 1990-2009. The index follws the OECD methodology and is directly comparable to it. Data were collected from questionnaires completed by teams of national experts and additional secondary sources.</gtr:description><gtr:id>F0B616B2-3E31-4652-ADB6-FCE7B383F159</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This database was used as a central component in two journal articles that I published in Socio-Economic Review and the British Journal of Industrial Relations (see the publication section). Furthermore, a number of researchers have asked for this data and have been using them in their analyses.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Employment protection legislation (EPL) index in central and eastern Europe, 1990-2009</gtr:title><gtr:type>Database/Collection of data</gtr:type><gtr:url>http://reshare.ukdataservice.ac.uk/850598/</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2012</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:description>This qualitative database provides an inventory of all employment protection reforms adopted in Central and Eastern European countries during 1990-2009. Each reform entry contains a short description of the reform and an indication of the scope (structural vs. marginal) and the direction (liberal vs. regulatory) of reform. The database follows the format of the Rodolfo de Benedetti and the Institute for Labour Studies (FRdB and IZA) Social Reforms Database for West European countries and is directly comparable to it. Data were collected from national laws, secondary literature, and questionnaires completed by teams of national experts.</gtr:description><gtr:id>E15F15E7-C1E8-4C33-9620-B02AFF13C5CC</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This database was used extensively in the analysis of an article I published in the European Political Science Review (see the publication section). The database has also informed the chapter I published in the Oxford Handbook of Employment Relations and the British Journal of Industrial Relations symposium that I co-edited with Colin Crouch.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Employment protection reforms in central and eastern Europe</gtr:title><gtr:type>Database/Collection of data</gtr:type><gtr:url>http://reshare.ukdataservice.ac.uk/850598/</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2012</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput></gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/10D6C5EB-0815-4EBC-9E44-99F351C72AD1"><gtr:id>10D6C5EB-0815-4EBC-9E44-99F351C72AD1</gtr:id><gtr:title>Partisanship, political constraints, and employment protection reforms in an era of austerity</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>European Political Science Review</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80